title: lodash/fp is heavy
body:
I never used the fp version of lodash before and thought I'd give it a go. Thankfully my build shows the package size and I noticed a 50KB increase of the minified file.

Here's a reduced test:

``` sh
$ echo "require('lodash/pick')" | browserify - | uglifyjs | gzip-size
2044
$ echo "require('lodash/fp/pick')" | browserify - | uglifyjs | gzip-size
22301
```

Not sure what can be done about it and it does look like the sudden increase only applies to the first `fp` import, but I ended up avoiding it and just using `obj => pick(obj, 'prop')` instead of `fpPick('prop')`

To easily see all the extra modules I used

``` sh
echo "require('lodash/fp/pick')" | browserify --full-paths - | uglifyjs | discify --open
```

title: _.update Last Element in Array

_.get(object, []) does not seem to return the object itself
body:
I expected this:

``` js
const root = {'a': 42};
_.get(root, []) === root; // => true
```

Instead, `undefined` is returned. I'm unsure if this is intentional behaviour; I cannot seem to find a github issue on this.

---

Fix for this seems to be to replace this line:
https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/84270a6a398d6ab065f8d1cf6901c5fc1da917ae/lodash.get/index.js#L466

with:

``` js
return (index >= 0 && index == length) ? object : undefined;
```

or simply,

``` js
return (index == length) ? object : undefined;
```

title: Not possible provide custom Cache to memoize
body:
Docs says:

> Note: The cache is exposed as the cache property on the memoized function. Its creation may be customized by replacing the _.memoize.Cache constructor with one whose instances implement the Map method interface of delete, get, has, and set.

So I'm trying to pass a custom Map-like to cache:

``` js
const mem = require('lodash/memoize')
mem.Cache = require('lru-cache')
```

The problem is that in the implementation `cache.has` is used before be assigned, so always I have `cache.has is not a function`.

Check [this](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/dist/lodash.js#L10235) line and [this](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/dist/lodash.js#L10244).

Strange "has" behavior with sparse arrays.
body:
I am seeing behavior I do not expect when using "has" with an object containing a sparse array.

``` Javascript
const _ = require('lodash')

const path = 'foo[2].a.b.c'
console.log(_.has({ foo: []}, path))
console.log(_.has({ foo: [0,1,]}, path))
console.log(_.has({ foo: [0,1,,]}, path))
```

outputs:

```
false
false
true
```

Seems odd to get that `true`.  Installed lodash@4.15.0 from npm, used node v6.2.0 to test, have seen the same in the browser.

title: why does does 'git pull' often fail to merge origin/master onto master in this repository?
body:
First off I should preface by saying that I don't actually use lodash myself -- it is included as part of a much larger project I work on.  I should also say I'm not really a Git expert (I have to RTFM almost every time I use it directly on the command line), though I do have a huge amount of experience with version control systems in general.

I frequently (3-10 times per week on at least two different systems) update a group of well over 40 repositories from github.com, lodash being one.  Many are quite active with daily changes, release branches, and so on.   I've only got the 'master' branch checked out in each, and I never make any changes of any kind in these repositories, and so normally my pulls result in fast-forward merges from 'origin/master'.

However lodash is the only one from this group that I regularly have trouble pulling (on both systems).  Quite regularly a pull fails with some kind of merge conflict.  Usually I remove the whole local repo and clone again (though I don't do this every time there's a problem -- I pull all the repos in this group with a script and I only fix things when I think the blast of errors from lodash might be obscuring some other error in another repo).

Today I tried to do a little more digging.

First I did this to try to clean up the mess (i.e. reset and move back to 'master'):

```
$ git status
# Not currently on any branch.
# Unmerged paths:
#   (use "git reset HEAD <file>..." to unstage)
#   (use "git add/rm <file>..." as appropriate to mark resolution)
#
#       both modified:      .travis.yml
#
no changes added to commit (use "git add" and/or "git commit -a")
$ git reset --hard HEAD
HEAD is now at 74fa09a Change category names of "Utility" to "Util" and "Chain" to "Seq".
$ git status
# Not currently on any branch.
nothing to commit (working directory clean)
$ git checkout master
Warning: you are leaving 3 commits behind, not connected to
any of your branches:

  74fa09a Change category names of "Utility" to "Util" and "Chain" to "Seq".
  a4385d6 Bump to v4.0.0.
  6135c5b Rebuild lodash and docs.

If you want to keep them by creating a new branch, this may be a good time
to do so with:

 git branch new_branch_name 74fa09aa3fbdbe59defe9dee9e5cd0da18610ccd

Switched to branch 'master'
Your branch and 'origin/master' have diverged,
and have 1 and 1362 different commits each, respectively.
```

So I did create a branch this time as suggested to see how/where it seemed to be in the history:

```
$ git branch what-the-heck 74fa09aa3fbdbe59defe9dee9e5cd0da18610ccd
```

Git log now shows me how this new branch fits into things:

```
* | commit ddd5318bb0075946284b76bccb0bf81ee63d1d26
| | Author: John-David Dalton <john.david.dalton@gmail.com>
| | Date:   Mon Jan 11 17:40:02 2016 -0800
| | 
| |     Change category names of "Utility" to "Util" and "Chain" to "Seq".
| |     
| | * commit 74fa09aa3fbdbe59defe9dee9e5cd0da18610ccd (refs/heads/what-the-heck)
| | | Author: John-David Dalton <john.david.dalton@gmail.com>
| | | Date:   Mon Jan 11 17:40:02 2016 -0800
| | | 
| | |     Change category names of "Utility" to "Util" and "Chain" to "Seq".
| | |    
| | * commit a4385d61cbbd2afee4793080c8b625e8f5c6a797
| | | Author: John-David Dalton <john.david.dalton@gmail.com>
| | | Date:   Sun Jan 10 13:44:36 2016 -0800
| | | 
| | |     Bump to v4.0.0.
| | |    
| | * commit 6135c5bd76e5d83623d8ace2defe24d2f8f65bc3
| |/  Author: John-David Dalton <john.david.dalton@gmail.com>
|/|   Date:   Sun Jan 10 13:43:51 2016 -0800
| |   
| |       Rebuild lodash and docs.
| |   
* | commit 3d44135df548fa22f36d16f50d28c884a62763ed
| | Author: John-David Dalton <john.david.dalton@gmail.com>
| | Date:   Mon Jan 11 16:13:32 2016 -0800
| | 
| |     Remove `run` alias.
| |   
```

I've not been able to reproduce the issues I'm having in a test repo, so I'm not exactly sure what's going wrong here.

I was thinking this was some kind of manual error combined with moving the 'master' ref from one branch to another, but given the identical timestamp on the two "identical" commits at the top of this section of the log, that seems less likely.  It does still look like there was an accidental commit after a release tag on a release branch, one that was repeated on the master branch again.  It would also seem that the 'master' ref was on that release branch at the time I did the last pull where everything worked normally.  The next time I pulled the 'master' ref seems to have moved and a commit with identical content is on the new 'master' branch, so trying to merge it with what I had last checked out fails and a fast-forward merge is not possible.

I may be completely wrong of course, but I would like to figure this out -- I've been having issues with pulling the lodash repository for many months now.

title: Provide `_.rangeStep` or similar in lodashfp
body:
When migrating from lodash to lodash/fp, one will need to convert any usages of `_.range(min, max, step)` to some new function, since the `_.range` exported by lodash/fp has a fixed arity of 2 and therefore will ignore the `step` parameter. (`_.rangeRight` also has a fixed arity of 2, so it isn't what we are looking for.) However, no such function is provided by lodash/fp. 

It would be nice if lodash/fp would export two new functions, for example `_.rangeStep` and `_.rangeStepRight`, that have a fixed arity of 3 and expect the `step` parameter to be provided.

title: Option to return [ ] with Nil values in castArray
body:
Hi!

When using `castArray` I found it very weird that it literally just wraps it's value in an array, not checking for `undefined` or `null` values. I was wondering since only the first value is considered for the _casting_ (`_.castArray(1,2,3) // [ 1 ]`), we could add an option to receive a function for which a `true` output should create an empty array:

```
_.castArray(undefiend) // [ undefined ]
_.castArray(undefiend, _.isNil) // [ ]
_.castArray(undefiend, _.isNull) // [ undefined ]
```

Or maybe a boolean?

title: Push into array - Performance
body:
Hi,

I'm sorry, this is definitely not an issue. Couldn't find any place to directly ask lodash developers so asking here.

Consider we have 2 very large arrays of size N and M,

```
 var array1 = [1,2,3...N],
       array2 = [a,b,c...M];
```

I want to push array2 to array1. 

Using native javascript, 
`Array.prototype.push.apply(array1,array2) 
`

Using lodash, I can do
`array1 = _.concat(array1,array2)
`

But concat will copy array1, so I guess it's performance will reduce by O(N). Is there any other way of pushing one array to another using lodash? or Is there any way to provide option to modify existing array to increase performance?

-Thanks

title: Also escape hyphens in escapeRegExp
body:
They're a special character in that they denote ranges, so if it is not escaped and ends up inside a character block like:

``` js
new RegExp(`[${_.escapeRegExp('a-z')}]`, 'g')
```

where the user is looking for a literal hyphen, the regex will return all letters a to z when the intent was the characters a, -, and z.

title: Docs: invalid signature of baseDelay return
